(4.) I am now arrived at his Fourth Argument. I ſhall crave leave to try the Strength of this too. He delivers himſelf thus, However meanly this way of making Melody in our Hearts to the Lord, may be thought by ſome; It has been certainly of above a Thouſand Years ſtanding in the Christian Church;
                  Ser. p. 13. 
                  And been received, and approved of by the Reformed, as well as the Popiſh Churches, (and therefore no part of Popery.)

But our Author will confute this. I Anſwer, ſaith he, It is no way repugnant to the moſt Spiritul Worſhip whatſoever;
                  Ser. p. 34. 
                  but ſo far from being prejudicial to it; that it is highly advantagious to make the Chriſtian Worſhip the more Spiritual, and to ſtir up the Affections of the Soul in order thereto.
